#compdef psd
# ============================================================================
# psd - Photoshop PSD file CLI: convert to PNG / extract text (Node)
#
# Author : kartsims
# Upstream: https://github.com/kartsims/psd-cli
# npm    : psd-cli (binary: psd)
#
# `psd` is the Node CLI for the `psd` library - a pure-JS
# Photoshop file parser. The CLI ingests one or more `.psd`
# files and can: convert each to a PNG (full-canvas
# composite), extract all text-layer content to a `.txt`
# file (preserving layer-tree paths), or open the converted
# PNG in the platform-default image viewer. Each input file
# is validated as a real PSD via magic-byte detection before
# the PSD library tries to parse it - skipping non-PSD files
# silently rather than crashing on an invalid header.
#
# Usage:
#   psd [options] <file...>
#
# Flags (commander):
#   -c, --convert      - convert to PNG named <FILENAME>.png
#   -t, --text         - extract text content to <FILENAME>.txt
#   -o, --open         - preview file after conversion
#                        (implicitly triggers --convert)
#   -V, --version      - print version
#   -h, --help         - print help
#
# The file-type lane is built on `file-type 3.3.0` (declared
# verbatim at upstream package.json HEAD), the canonical Node
# magic-byte file-type detector by Sindre Sorhus
# (github.com/sindresorhus/file-type, 1700+ stars). file-type
# is the most-downloaded MIME-detection package on npm (~30
# million weekly downloads). The detection model is the same
# magic-byte-table pattern as the Rust + Go lanes: read the
# first 4100 bytes of a stream, match against a precompiled
# signature table, return the canonical `{ ext, mime }`
# pair. The library supports 200+ formats covering every
# IANA-registered image / video / audio / archive / font /
# document type. psd-cli uses it to validate input files
# before delegating to the heavyweight PSD parser - the
# psd library throws on malformed input, but file-type
# returns null cheaply, letting the CLI skip + log instead
# of crashing.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 231 :: File-type / MIME detection from magic bytes  [CLOSES]
# Round 1393 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 231 (224th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : bojand/infer                 [R1391 _lit]
#   Go      : gabriel-vasile/mimetype      [R1392 _gitness]
#   TS/Node : sindresorhus/file-type       [R1393 THIS FILE]
#
# file-type is structurally interesting: it is the canonical
# Sindre Sorhus library in this axis - the same author who
# maintains roughly 1500 of the most-downloaded npm packages
# (chalk, ora, got, p-limit, p-map, slugify, ...). Sindre's
# packages share a consistent design philosophy (minimal API
# surface, ESM-first, async-iterator-friendly, "do one thing
# well"), and the npm ecosystem has settled into a pattern
# where Sindre's package is the canonical answer to any
# narrow utility need. file-type fits that pattern: the API
# is a single async function `fileTypeFromBlob(blob)` (or
# fromBuffer / fromStream / fromTokenizer), the package
# exports no opinions about how you should use it, and the
# README is the implicit RFC for "how should I detect file
# types in Node."
#
# The three-lane structural commentary across Axis 231:
# every implementation maintains its OWN magic-byte signature
# table - the tables are not shared as a published artifact
# between projects. infer, mimetype, and file-type each
# import the IANA registry + extend it with format-specific
# heuristics. Byte-for-byte agreement on the 200+ common
# formats happens because the magic bytes ARE the IANA
# specification (RFC 2046 + RFC 6838 + per-format RFCs); no
# library can disagree on what bytes mean. The libraries
# differ in API shape (Rust returns Option<Type>, Go
# returns *MIME with method chain, Node returns async result)
# but the underlying detection model is byte-for-byte
# interoperable.
# ============================================================================

_psd() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-c --convert)'{-c,--convert}'[convert to PNG named <FILENAME>.png]' \
        '(-t --text)'{-t,--text}'[extract text content to <FILENAME>.txt]' \
        '(-o --open)'{-o,--open}'[preview file after conversion (implies --convert)]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '*:Photoshop file:_files -g "*.psd"'
}

_psd "$@"
